<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the formula for calculating horsepower?", answer: "Horsepower is calculated using the formula HP = (Torque x RPM) / 5252, where torque is measured in pound-feet (lb-ft) and RPM is revolutions per minute. The constant 5252 comes from the definition of one horsepower (33,000 ft-lbs per minute) divided by 2 * pi. This formula shows that HP and torque are always equal at exactly 5,252 RPM." },
  { question: "What is the difference between horsepower and torque?", answer: "Torque is the rotational force the engine produces, measured in pound-feet (lb-ft) or Newton-meters (Nm). Horsepower is the rate at which that work is done, combining torque with engine speed. Think of torque as the ability to push or pull, while horsepower is how quickly that pushing or pulling happens. An engine can have high torque at low RPM but still produce less horsepower than a high-revving engine with less torque." },
  { question: "How do I convert horsepower to kilowatts?", answer: "To convert mechanical horsepower to kilowatts, multiply by 0.7457. For example, 300 HP x 0.7457 = 223.7 kW. To convert kilowatts back to horsepower, divide by 0.7457 or multiply by 1.341. This conversion is useful when comparing vehicles from countries using different power measurement systems." },
  { question: "What is a good horsepower for a car?", answer: "For daily driving, 150-200 HP is adequate for most sedans. Sporty cars typically have 250-350 HP. Performance vehicles range from 400-600 HP, and supercars exceed 700 HP. The right amount depends on vehicle weight, intended use, and personal preference. A lightweight 200 HP car can feel faster than a heavy 300 HP SUV." },
  { question: "Why do horsepower and torque cross at 5252 RPM?", answer: "The crossover at 5,252 RPM is a mathematical certainty, not a coincidence. Since HP = (Torque x RPM) / 5252, when RPM equals 5,252, the equation simplifies to HP = Torque. Below 5,252 RPM, torque is always numerically higher than horsepower. Above 5,252 RPM, horsepower is numerically higher. This crossover point appears on every dyno chart regardless of engine type." }
]) %>

